# ADR 0001: Initial Architecture

## Status

Accepted

## Context

This project was initialized using archseed with the following stack decisions. This ADR records the architectural foundation and the rationale behind each choice.

## Decisions

{{if .Features.Backend}}
### Backend: {{.Stack.Backend.Language}} / {{.Stack.Backend.Framework}}{{if .Stack.Backend.Router}} ({{.Stack.Backend.Router}}){{end}}

- **Language**: {{if eq .Stack.Backend.Language "go"}}Go 1.26+ — strong typing, excellent standard library, fast compilation, built-in concurrency, and single-binary deployment. Ideal for API services and microservices.{{else if eq .Stack.Backend.Framework "nestjs"}}TypeScript with NestJS — mature ecosystem, dependency injection out of the box, decorator-based controllers, and strong typing for large-scale applications.{{end}}
{{if .Stack.Backend.Router}}- **Router**: {{.Stack.Backend.Router}} — lightweight, idiomatic, and performant HTTP routing.{{end}}{{if .Stack.Backend.ORM}}
- **ORM**: {{.Stack.Backend.ORM}} — type-safe database access with schema migration support.{{end}}{{if .Stack.Backend.APIContract}}
- **API Contract**: {{.Stack.Backend.APIContract}} — language-agnostic contract definition enabling client generation and documentation automation.{{end}}
{{end}}
{{if .Features.Frontend}}
### Frontend: {{.Stack.Frontend.Framework}} / {{.Stack.Frontend.Styling}} ({{.Stack.Frontend.BuildTool}})

{{if eq .Stack.Frontend.Framework "react"}}- **Framework**: React — component-based UI, large ecosystem, and widespread tooling support.{{else if eq .Stack.Frontend.Framework "next"}}- **Framework**: Next.js — React-based full-stack framework with SSR, file-based routing, and optimized builds.{{else if eq .Stack.Frontend.Framework "remix"}}- **Framework**: Remix — React-based framework focused on web standards, nested routing, and progressive enhancement.{{else}}- **Framework**: Vanilla JS — minimal dependencies, suitable for simple static interfaces.{{end}}
{{if ne .Stack.Frontend.Styling "css"}}- **Styling**: {{.Stack.Frontend.Styling}} — utility-first CSS framework for rapid and consistent UI development.{{else}}- **Styling**: Plain CSS — zero dependencies, full control over styles.{{end}}
{{if ne .Stack.Frontend.BuildTool "none"}}- **Build Tool**: {{.Stack.Frontend.BuildTool}}{{end}}
{{end}}
{{if .Features.Database}}
### Database: {{.Stack.Database.Primary}}

{{if eq .Stack.Database.Primary "postgres"}}- **PostgreSQL** — mature relational database with strong ACID compliance, JSON support, and excellent ecosystem of extensions. Chosen for reliability, performance, and production readiness.{{else if eq .Stack.Database.Primary "mysql"}}- **MySQL** — widely adopted relational database with strong performance, replication support, and broad hosting compatibility.{{else if eq .Stack.Database.Primary "sqlite"}}- **SQLite** — embedded, serverless database. Ideal for local development, single-user applications, and scenarios where zero configuration is preferred.{{else if eq .Stack.Database.Primary "mongodb"}}- **MongoDB** — document-oriented NoSQL database with flexible schema, horizontal scaling, and rich query language. Ideal for applications with evolving data models and rapid iteration.{{else if eq .Stack.Database.Primary "dynamodb"}}- **DynamoDB** — fully managed NoSQL key-value and document database with single-digit millisecond performance at any scale. Schema-less design with automatic partitioning and replication.{{end}}
{{if .Stack.Database.Cache}}
- **Cache**: {{.Stack.Database.Cache}} — in-memory data store for high-throughput reads and session management.{{end}}
{{if .Stack.Database.ObjectStorage}}
- **Object Storage**: {{.Stack.Database.ObjectStorage}} — S3-compatible object storage for file and blob data.{{end}}
{{end}}
{{if .Features.Auth}}
### Authentication
{{if eq .Stack.Auth.Provider "custom"}}
- **Provider**: Custom (JWT)
- JWT-based authentication implemented end-to-end. Backend issues and validates tokens, frontend manages token storage and attachment to requests. No external identity provider required.
{{else}}
- **Provider**: {{.Stack.Auth.Provider}} ({{.Stack.Auth.Protocol}})
- Industry-standard protocol for delegated authentication.
{{end}}
{{end}}
{{if .Features.Queue}}
### Message Queue: {{.Stack.Messaging.Provider}}

- Reliable message broker for async processing, event-driven workflows, and service decoupling.
{{end}}
{{if .Features.Observability}}
### Observability

- Structured logging, metrics collection (Prometheus), and distributed tracing (OpenTelemetry) for production monitoring and debugging.
{{end}}
### CI/CD

- **Provider**: {{.Quality.CI.Provider}}
- **Required checks**: {{if .Quality.CI.RequiredChecks}}{{range $i, $c := .Quality.CI.RequiredChecks}}{{if $i}}, {{end}}{{$c}}{{end}}{{else}}lint, test, build{{end}}

## Consequences

### Positive

- {{if .Features.Backend}}Consistent backend architecture that is familiar to Go/TypeScript developers{{end}}{{if and .Features.Backend .Features.Frontend}} and{{end}}{{if .Features.Frontend}} component-based frontend with modern tooling{{end}}.
- Documented stack decisions reduce onboarding time for new developers and AI agents.
- CI/CD pipeline ensures code quality and prevents regressions.
- The monorepo structure simplifies dependency management and cross-team collaboration.

### Negative

- Stack migration becomes a documented process requiring a new ADR.
- Teams must follow the established architecture patterns unless a new ADR justifies changes.
- Initial setup time is higher than ad-hoc approaches, but this investment pays back in consistency.

## Alternatives Considered

{{if .Features.Backend}}{{if eq .Stack.Backend.Language "go"}}- **Node.js/Express**: Rejected in favor of Go for better performance, simpler deployment, and stronger typing.{{end}}{{if eq .Stack.Backend.Framework "nestjs"}}- **Go/Chi or Go/net-http**: Rejected in favor of NestJS for teams more familiar with TypeScript and the Node.js ecosystem.{{end}}{{end}}
{{if .Features.Frontend}}{{if eq .Stack.Frontend.Framework "react"}}- **Next.js**: Offers SSR out of the box but introduces additional complexity. React with Vite was chosen for simpler client-side rendering needs.{{end}}{{if eq .Stack.Frontend.Framework "vanilla"}}- **React/Vue**: Rejected to keep the stack minimal and dependency-free for this project's requirements.{{end}}{{end}}
{{if eq .Stack.Database.Primary "postgres"}}- **MySQL**: Comparable feature set; PostgreSQL was preferred for superior JSON support, indexing, and extension ecosystem.{{else if eq .Stack.Database.Primary "mysql"}}- **PostgreSQL**: Comparable feature set; MySQL was preferred for wider hosting support and simpler operational experience.{{else if eq .Stack.Database.Primary "sqlite"}}- **PostgreSQL/MySQL**: Rejected due to operational overhead — SQLite is sufficient for the project's data needs and eliminates database server management.{{else if eq .Stack.Database.Primary "mongodb"}}- **PostgreSQL/MySQL**: Rejected in favor of MongoDB for flexible document schemas and simpler horizontal scaling needs.{{else if eq .Stack.Database.Primary "dynamodb"}}- **PostgreSQL/MongoDB**: Rejected in favor of DynamoDB for serverless compatibility and zero-operations scaling.{{end}}
